        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-07-23 12:40:19.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified-1\n\nThis does not seem to utilize aaf for the authorizations",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "7e9a79bf6c4a949ce6e195c5fa4b973cd2d108f5",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2085,
          "name": "Byung-Woo Jun",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "byung-woo.jun@est.tech",
          "username": "byungwoojun"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-07-23 13:02:54.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review\n\nHi Steve, AAF authorization or authentication? Does AAF support URL-pattern based authorization? If we get the AAF-way of authentication and authorization examples, it would be great.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "668cc84aac73869fc2d3850c497504d4022e8db4",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 63,
          "name": "Steve Smokowski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "ss835w@att.com",
          "username": "SteveSmokowski"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-07-23 13:04:19.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1: -Code-Review\n> \n> Hi Steve, AAF authorization or authentication? Does AAF support URL-pattern based authorization? If we get the AAF-way of authentication and authorization examples, it would be great.\n\nIt supports pattern based url Authorization.  I have been a bit buried under other work.  I will try to push out a sample.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "dcdb2f7d233df22f0802d5152dd12920e98ebda4",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5269,
          "name": "Michael Morris",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "michael.morris@est.tech",
          "username": "MichaelMorris"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-07-25 11:30:24.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Steve, the focus of this is authentication rather than authorization. For El Alto we are planning to make use of spring boot support for authentication.\nWe can of course consider moving to using AAF when we get a better understanding of how to use AAF to perform the authentication that we require (TLS with tokens, two way TLS, TLS with basic auth) and a better understanding of how an AAF based solution will work with an external component (VNFM)",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "b8e17aebdbb4ccfb929228d83b5d46c8030d30d7",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2085,
          "name": "Byung-Woo Jun",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "byung-woo.jun@est.tech",
          "username": "byungwoojun"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-07-25 13:28:24.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Steve, here is my two cents... The reason I asked you if the concern is about  authentication or authorization is that authorization support properly is not trivial. It is good that AAF supports the URL-pattern based authorization. To me, it is a coarse-grained authorization. AAF documentation said it supports fine-grained authorization, but I need to know more details.\nAlso, authorization is enforced by the service provider (e.g., PEP, PDP) based on the roles, attributes or policies (RBAC, ABAC, PBAC). AAF can control the ONAP internal components, but in this case, we are dealing with external vendor SVNFM, so the vendors have their own authorization mechanisms. In short, we need a better understanding of AAF and overall ONAP authentication and authorization strategy.   Maybe, we approve this as the first step and open another discussion for security. Then, we apply the common solution to the whole ONAP SO. Once you share AT&T security design and implementation, we can review together.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
